pe\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing dynamic class loading**\\n\\nI'm examining the MethodHandles.Lookup.defineHiddenClass, thinking about whether the class loader is the same as the lookup. Using instrumentation to append to the bootstrap seems inappropriate. Should I avoid dynamic loading in tests? The rules mention catching unsupported features tied to dynamic class loading. Creating a custom class loader for a provider copy could be tricky. I wonder if dynamic class loading might be a public API. I need to ensure execution reaches the relevant calls while considering the limitations on using reflection and testing under native conditions.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering dynamic class loading**\\n\\nI’m looking at the Class.forName branch and realize it might only refer to a public API. Could a dynamic-class-loading pattern be allowed? The rules state that if a test's behavior fundamentally requires open-ended dynamic class loading—like with classes, JARs, or other definitions discovered after building the native executable—I may need to catch errors, verify them, and then rethrow if unsupported. Wait, does this mean if it's unsupported, I shouldn't rethrow? I need clarity on this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Refining instantiation**\\n\\nI realize I need to add an instantiation because there isn’t an existing placeholder. This seems to cover two bases. I'm considering whether class.forName should stay in the mix, as it might still be acceptable. But according to the task, I should refine what I have. It might be necessary to test the getProvider method using the class name too. I think searching through existing BC tests could help me find useful references.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_4ALjRoHGI3YNw9pwKv6GdSRt|fc_0e398141afbd4c2a0169fbbeb4aab4819c8e10d5926f9400e5", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src -path '*bcprov*' -name '*.java' -print | head -50"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "p